Mathematical model

We indicate with \(\mathcal{L}\left(\cdot\right)\) a fully connected layer in which all neurons are based on the MAM paradigm (1). We consider networks with \(N\) inputs collected in the vector \(\bm{x}=\left(x_{1},\dots,x_{N}\right)\), two MAM hidden layers producing a vector \(\bm{z}\left(\bm{x}\right)=\left(z_{1}(\bm{x}),z_{2}(\bm{x}),\dots\right)= \mathcal{L}^{\prime\prime}\left(\mathcal{L}^{\prime}\left(\bm{x}\right)\right)\) and a single output \(Z\left(\bm{x}\right)\in\mathbb{R}\) produced by a final layer that computes either the normalized linear combination

\[Z\left(\bm{x}\right)=\frac{\sum_{k}c_{k}z_{k}(\bm{x})}{\sum_{k}z_{k}(\bm{x})}\] (2)

or the linear combination

\[Z\left(\bm{x}\right)=\sum_{k}c_{k}z_{k}(\bm{x})\] (3)

We normalize the input domain by assuming \(x_{i}\in\mathbb{X}=\left[0,1\right]\) for \(i=1,\dots,N\) and indicate with \(\mathcal{Z}^{*}\) the family of functions in (2) while with \(\mathcal{Z}\) the analogous family of functions in (3). Smoothness conditions on our target functions \(f:\mathbb{X}^{N}\mapsto\mathbb{R}\) is formalized by assuming that they belong to \(\mathcal{C}^{d}\left(\mathbb{X}^{N}\right)\), i.e., that their \(d\)-th order derivatives are continuous. Distances between functions are measured by means of the norms defined as

\[\left\|\phi\right\|_{k,p}=\left[\int_{\mathbb{X}^{N}}\left|\phi(x)\right|^{p} \mathrm{d}x+k\sum_{j=1}^{N}\int_{\mathbb{X}^{N}}\left|\frac{\partial\phi}{x_{j }}(x)\right|^{p}\mathrm{d}x\right]^{1/p}\]

with \(k=\left\{0,1\right\}\) and \(p\geq 1\).

## 3 Main results

Within the above framework, we prove two theorems that describe the universal approximation properties of DNNs using MAM neurons in the hidden layers.

**Theorem 1**.: _For any function \(f\in\mathcal{C}^{0}\left(\mathbb{X}^{N}\right)\) and any prescribed level of tolerance \(\epsilon>0\), there is a \(Z\in\mathcal{Z}^{*}\) such that \(\left\|f-Z\right\|_{0,\infty}\leq\epsilon\)._

**Theorem 2**.: _For any function \(f\in\mathcal{C}^{2}\left(\mathbb{X}^{N}\right)\), any prescribed level of tolerance \(\epsilon>0\) and finite \(p\geq 1\), there is a \(Z\in\mathcal{Z}\) such that \(\left\|f-Z\right\|_{1,p}\leq\epsilon\)._

The proofs of both theorems are reported in Section 6 and are constructive. In particular, subnetworks in the cascade \(\bm{z}\left(\bm{x}\right)=\mathcal{L}^{\prime\prime}\left(\mathcal{L}^{\prime }\left(\bm{x}\right)\right)\) are identified and programmed to make each \(z_{k}(\bm{x})\) a weakly unimodal piecewise-linear function of the inputs, whose maximum is \(1\) and is reached in a hyperrectangular subset of the domain, while the function vanishes for points far from the center of that hyper-rectangle. The shapes and positions of these functions can then be designed along with the values of the weights \(c_{k}\) so that their combination by means of either (2) or (3) is capable of approximating the target function arbitrarily well as measured either by \(\left\|\cdot\right\|_{1,p}\) or \(\left\|\cdot\right\|_{0,\infty}\).

