### Network construction

The aim of this subsection is to show that our network can be programmed to make the outputs of the second hidden layer specific weakly unimodal piecewise-linear functions \(z_{k}\left(\bm{x}\right)\) of the inputs.

**Lemma 1**.: _Let \(z\) be any of the outputs of the second hidden layer. For \(N>1\) and any choice of the quantities \(\omega_{1},\ldots,\omega_{N}\in\left[0,1\right]\), \(l_{1},\ldots,l_{N}\geq 0\), \(\delta_{1}^{c},\ldots,\delta_{N}^{c}\geq 0\), and \(\delta_{1}^{a},\ldots,\delta_{N}^{s}\geq 0\), the two MAM hidden layers can be programmed to yield_

\[z\left(\bm{x}\right)=\left[1-\Delta\left(\bm{x}\right)\right]^{+}\] (5)

_where_

\[\Delta\left(\bm{x}\right)=\max_{i\in\left\{1,\ldots,N\right\}}\left\{0,\frac{ \left|x_{i}-\omega_{i}\right|-l_{i}}{\left\{\delta_{i}^{i}\quad\text{if }x_{i}<\omega_{i} \right.\right.}}\right\}\] (6)

Proof of Lemma 1.: We assume that neurons in the first hidden layer come in pairs \(\left(y_{1}^{k},y_{1}^{k},y_{2}^{k},y_{2}^{k},\ldots\right)=\mathcal{L}^{ \prime}(\bm{x})\) and the output of a pair depends on only one of the inputs.

Without any loss of generality, we assume that \(y_{i}^{\text{\tiny L}}\) and \(y_{i}^{\text{\tiny R}}\) depend only on \(x_{i}\) for \(i=1,\ldots,N\) while all the other \(N-1\) input weights are set to \(0\). The other outputs of the first hidden layer are involved in the computation of the outputs of the second hidden layer further to the \(z\) we are considering.

For \(y_{i}^{\text{\tiny L}}\) the non-null input weight is equal to \(\nicefrac{{-1}}{{\delta_{i}^{\text{\tiny L}}}}\) and the bias is \(\nicefrac{{(\omega_{i}-l_{i})}}{{\delta_{i}^{\text{\tiny L}}}}\), while for \(y_{i}^{\text{\tiny R}}\) the non-null input weight is equal to \(\nicefrac{{1}}{{\delta_{i}^{\text{\tiny R}}}}\) and bias is \(\nicefrac{{(-\omega_{i}-l_{i})}}{{\delta_{i}^{\text{\tiny R}}}}\). By recalling (1) one gets

\[y_{i}^{\text{\tiny L}}=\left[\frac{-x_{i}+\omega_{i}-l_{i}}{\delta_{i}^{\text{ \tiny L}}}\right]^{+}\quad\text{and}\quad y_{i}^{\text{\tiny R}}=\left[\frac{ x_{i}-\omega_{i}-l_{i}}{\delta_{i}^{\text{\tiny R}}}\right]^{+}\] (7)

In the second hidden layer, the neuron computing the \(z\) we consider has all input weights equal to \(0\) but those connecting to \(y_{1}^{k},y_{1}^{k},\ldots,y_{N}^{k},y_{N}^{\text{\tiny R}}\). Non-null input weights are equal to \(-1\) and the bias is \(1\) so that\[z=\left[\max_{i\in\left\{1,\ldots,N\right\}}\left\{0,-y_{i}^{k},-y_{i}^{k}\right\} +\min_{i\in\left\{1,\ldots,N\right\}}\left\{0,-y_{i}^{k},-y_{i}^{k}\right\}+1 \right]^{+}=\left[1-\max_{i\in\left\{1,\ldots,N\right\}}\left\{y_{i}^{k},y_{i}^ {k}\right\}\right]^{+}\] (8)

Considering the last expression, note that, if \(x_{i}\geq\omega_{i}\) then \(y_{i}^{k}\geq 0\) and \(y_{i}^{k}=0\) while, if \(x_{i}<\omega_{i}\) then \(y_{i}^{k}=0\) and \(y_{i}^{k}\geq 0\). Hence, without loss of generality, we may assume that \(x_{i}\geq\omega_{i}\) for \(i=1,\ldots,N\), being all other cases a variation of this one by suitable symmetry and scaling. With this, \(y_{i}^{k}=0\) for \(i=1,\ldots,N\) and (8) becomes

\[z=\left[1-\max_{i=1,\ldots,N}\left[\frac{x_{i}-\omega_{i}-l_{i}}{\delta_{i}^{ k}}\right]^{+}\right]^{+}=\left[1-\max_{i=1,\ldots,N}\left\{0,\frac{x_{i}-\omega_{i }-l_{i}}{\delta_{i}^{k}}\right\}\right]^{+}\] (9)

that is equivalent to the thesis. 

To interpret Lemma 1 note that \(\Delta(\bm{x})\) is a scaled measure of how far the input vector \(\bm{x}\) is from the hyper-rectangle centered at \(\bm{\omega}=\left(\omega_{1},\ldots,\omega_{N}\right)\) with sides \(2l_{1},\ldots,2l_{N}\). Hence, \(z\left(\bm{x}\right)\) is maximum and equal to \(1\) if \(\bm{x}\) belongs to such a hyper-rectangle and has a piecewise-linear decreasing profile when \(\bm{x}\) gets further from \(\bm{\omega}\). Figure 2 reports an example of a \(z\left(\bm{x}\right)\) when \(N=2\).

In the following, we will assume that each neuron in the second hidden layer matches a whole subnetwork as implied by Lemma 1. With this, we may re-index the outputs of the second hidden layer as \(z_{\bm{\omega}}\left(\bm{x}\right)\) associating each of them with the center of the hyper-rectangle in which \(z_{\bm{\omega}}\left(\bm{x}\right)=1\). The same is done with the corresponding weights \(c_{\bm{\omega}}\) in the output layers.

