### Universal approximation properties with linear output neuron

In this case, the approximation capabilities of our network over the whole domain depend on the local behaviour of subnetworks converging not in a single second-hidden-layer neuron but in \(2N\) second-hidden-layer neurons.

Formally, given a center \(\bm{\omega}\in\mathbb{X}^{N}\) we include in a subnetwork neurons of the second hidden layer with outputs labelled \(z_{\bm{\omega}^{1-}},z_{\bm{\omega}^{1+}}\),...,\(z_{\bm{\omega}^{N-}},z_{\bm{\omega}^{N+}}\) as well as all the previous neurons needed to compute such outputs.

The expression of each \(z_{\bm{\omega}^{j,k}}\) is given by Lemma 1 and thus is defined by the center point \(\bm{\omega}^{j\pm}=(\omega_{1}^{j\pm},\ldots,\omega_{N}^{j\pm})\), by the slopes \(\delta_{1}^{\iota,j\pm},\ldots,\delta_{N}^{\iota,j\pm}\) and \(\delta_{1}^{\kappa,j\pm},\ldots,\delta_{N}^{\kappa,j\pm}\), as well as by the side lengths \(l_{1}^{j\pm},\ldots,l_{N}^{j\pm}\).

